    <exploration>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Suppose that an explosion occurs at the origin <m>(0,0,0)</m>. Heat from the explosion starts to radiate outwards. Now suppose that a few moments after the explosion, the temperature at any point in space is given by <m>w=T(x,y,z)=100-x^2-y^2-z^2.</m>
        </p>
      </introduction>

      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Which points in space have a temperature of 99? Use algebra to simplify this to <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=1</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <hint>
          <p>
            What does the 99 replace in your function?
          </p>
        </hint>
      </task>
      <task>
        <p>
